issue.title: In some cases lldpd cannot get all interfaces
issue.body:
# lldpcli -vv
admin@sutc-a02-40u-bizleaf0101:~$ lldpcli -v
1.0.5
```

# Bug description
Create many interfaces on the device, including vlan, lag, eth, and vxlan. The number exceeds a thousand. Start lldpd repeatedly and execute lldpcli show interface detail. Sometimes only some of the created interfaces are displayed.
## Steps to reproduce the problem

comment.body:
I looked at the code. It should be that during initialization, when receiving the GETLINK message, the receiving process was interrupted by a notification from the kernel.
![image](https://github.com/lldpd/lldpd/assets/107174759/a59ff89d-e1e7-4e49-ae9d-d62177ef9146)

Receiving a message without the NLM_F_MULTI flag causes recv to exit.
```

comment.body: I've added back the parsing part of 802.3bt.

commits.message:
daemon/lldp: restore read support for 802.3BT

As it was said to work for most people, let's keep it. Just remove write
support for now.

issue.title: src/client/conf-power.c: Add support for 803.2bt parameters.
issue.body: This patch adds support for the 802.3bt parameters to lldpcli.

comment.body: After trying to add some tests, I discovered that 802.3bt support in lldpd was broken since the beginning. I don't know exactly why, but the TLV generated had an incorrect length. After digging a bit more, it seems Wireshark does not agree on everything present in the TLV. Maybe the support introduced in #350 was good enough to parse, but the sending part was not tested? Or maybe it's based on an earlier version of the standard? As the standard is not freely available, it is difficult for me to check. I am not comfortable maintaining something broken. The work previously done is still present in the history in case someone want to dig a bit.

commits.message:
client/conf-power: Add support for 803.2bt parameters.

Signed-off-by: Andreas Hofmann <git@andreas-hofmann.org>

daemon/protocols: fix some 802.3bt stuff

And add some tests.

daemon/lldp: remove support for 802.3bt

It was broken and despite a tentative to fix it, it is unknown if this
is correct. This looks different from the code in Wireshark. Maybe it
was done on an earlier version of 802.3bt? As the standard is not freely
available, I cannot reasonably fix it.

lib: bump API/ABI

Due to previous change, it seems safer to bump the API/ABI as it would
be easy to reuse the numbers introduced by 802.3bt.

Fix #404 (as a side-effect)
